TI  - Effect of High-Dose Vitamin D Supplementation on All-Cause Mortality: A 
      Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis of Randomized Clinical Trials.
PG  - 1355-1366
LID - 10.1001/jama.2023.17009 [doi]
AB  - IMPORTANCE: Whether high-dose vitamin D supplementation reduces all-cause 
      mortality remains uncertain despite numerous randomized clinical trials. 
      OBJECTIVE: To examine the association between high-dose vitamin D 
      supplementation and all-cause mortality. DATA SOURCES: MEDLINE, Embase, 
      Cochrane Central Register of Controlled Trials, and ClinicalTrials.gov 
      searched from inception to August 2023. STUDY SELECTION: Randomized 
      clinical trials comparing high-dose vitamin D supplementation with lower 
      doses or placebo in adults. DATA EXTRACTION AND SYNTHESIS: Two 
      independent reviewers extracted data and assessed risk of bias. 
      MAIN OUTCOMES AND MEASURES: All-cause mortality was the primary outcome. 
      RESULTS: Fifty-three trials enrolling 94 148 participants were included. 
      High-dose vitamin D did not reduce all-cause mortality compared with 
      controls (relative risk, 0.97; 95% CI, 0.93-1.02; P = .23). 
      CONCLUSIONS AND RELEVANCE: High-dose vitamin D supplementation does not 
      appear to reduce all-cause mortality.
