TI  - Antibody-drug conjugates: the new frontier in targeted cancer therapy.
PG  - 463-482
LID - 10.1038/s41573-023-00651-z [doi]
AB  - Antibody-drug conjugates (ADCs) represent a rapidly evolving class of 
      targeted therapeutics that combine the specificity of monoclonal antibodies 
      with the cytotoxic potency of small-molecule drugs. Recent approvals of 
      multiple ADCs across a broad range of tumour types have validated this 
      approach and invigorated the field. Here we review the principles of ADC 
      design, mechanisms of action and resistance, and the latest clinical data 
      for approved and late-stage ADCs. We also discuss emerging strategies to 
      enhance therapeutic windows and expand indications, including novel linker 
      chemistry, site-specific conjugation and combination approaches.
